metadata.name: Concrete #457
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Henge #319
metadata.description:
Henge is an exploration of circular megalithic structures of the prehistoric age. It is a work of historical fiction where these stone assemblies, achieved through herculean efforts of stacking, aligning, and balancing immense chiseled rocks, are reimagined within an alternate universe of algorithmic possibility. Historically, henges share a few qualities that inspired this project. First, they are places of gathering within a loose collection of stones to organize ceremony or worship under celestial alignments. They are also monolithic in their materiality and employ the most elemental techniques of megalithic, or large stone, construction. These particular types of henges, known as cromlechs, are circular spaces fit with purpose and ritual and in this sense, serve as precedents to the great human edifices; charging landscapes with meaning and presence through geometry and order. Finally, henges are a collective language of place-making shared across a range of cultures and ages, from the Mesolithic and Neolithic eras and across territories from modern-day Morocco, Portugal, Brazil, Germany, Scandinavia, to the well-known Stonehenge in Great Britain.

This project is deeply inspired by the timeless and universal narrative created through the thoughtful and deliberate placement of large rocks in a circle. It seems that when confronted with marking a place and communing with nature, human beings like to make circles out of stones. Among all the symbols of place making, the circle is the original and still remains the most universal. Through the use of code to portray these imperfect structures, Henge animates the history of these circles in all their roughness and seemingly endless variation.


--------

Created by Aranda\Lasch @ArandaLasch
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art
November 2022

[Interaction instructions]
'left' + 'right' arrow keys to change view
'i' saves a 2048x2048 PNG

[Info]
p5.js
Henge is optimized for Chrome, runs slowly on Firefox (the longer the wait, the more stones and/or grass are being generated)

metadata.name: Punktwelt #96
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Asterium #246
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: #symmetriClew #32
metadata.description:
Thank you for adding me to your collection. Now that I’m a part of your tez fam, please open me in live view, enter ‘9’ or ‘10’, wait, press ‘P’, print me, put me on your wall, and enjoy.

#symmetriClew is a special collection inspired by, and in honor of, Clew #205.  Clew #205 is the only symmetrical #lostNotLost output in the 567-piece Clew collection.   A brief write up on #symmetriClew can be found at https://abstractment.art/symmetriclew.

Similar to Clew, this collection is designed for your wall.

When opening live view, you’ll be prompted to choose a render quality (1 for lowest; 10 for highest). The higher quality renders are for printing and zooming in to choose your own sub-composition or explore the details. Higher quality images will naturally take longer to render but will be worth the wait, especially if seeking to print. If you find a partial render particularly nice, you can press spacebar to pause (and unpause). Save a PNG by pressing ‘P’ or a JPEG with ‘J’. Medium and high quality renders are optimized for Chrome desktop and may not function on other browsers or mobile devices.

Thumbnail previews will render at lower quality.  Please keep in mind that I’m best enjoyed in live view.

created using p5js

#symmetriClew
abstractment, 2022

metadata.name: fx(splash) #25
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.

metadata.name: Act One #42
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says “take me home and I will dance for you forever”.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 2.0

Created by elsif, 2022.11.

metadata.name: Absorbed #321
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF’s Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT™). 

MAT™ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT™. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed – high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and “sinusoidal” noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists’ belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica’s companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.
